{"timestamp": "2025-12-01 16:46:24.465632", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report\nDate: (current capture)\n\nSummary (executive)\n- Control plane (BGP) is functioning: all FRR routers have established EBGP neighbors and the expected /24 host prefixes (10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24) are present in BGP tables across the fabric.\n- Data plane is impaired: host-to-host ICMP is intermittent or failing. Observed symptoms include 50% packet loss from pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1 and a complete timeout on the reverse flow (pc_0_1 -> pc_0_0) during active tests.\n- The problem appears to be in the data plane (forwarding/edge) rather than the control plane (routing), because BGP sessions and route distribution look healthy. The most likely area implicated is the leaf-edge connectivity or per-host reachability (the leaf-to-host edge or ARP/forwarding on the leaf interfaces), but there are multiple plausible causes — see evidence and hypotheses below.\n\nObserved data and key findings\n1) Host configuration and reachability (pc_0_0, pc_0_1)\n- pc_0_0: IP 10.0.0.2/24; default route via 10.0.0.1.\n- pc_0_1: IP 10.0.1.2/24; default route via 10.0.1.1.\n- Ping results:\n  - pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1: 4 transmitted, 2 received, 50% packet loss; rtt avg ~3.0 ms.\n  - pc_0_1 -> pc_0_0: ping command timed out (no replies within tool timeout).\n- Attempts to ping the leaf gateway IPs from PCs produced tool errors in some automated attempts (tool reported \"Device `10.0.0.1`/`10.0.1.1` is not running\" in some contexts). Manual inspection of router interfaces shows those IPs are present and interfaces are UP on leaf routers, so the tool error is likely an artifact of the test harness rather than definitive proof the interfaces are down.\n\n2) Router interfaces and routes (leaf, spine, super-spine)\n- All router interfaces relevant to the topology are configured and in state UP (ip addr / ifconfig outputs show the /31 inter-router links and leaf-to-host /24s).\n- Example leaf interfaces:\n  - leaf_router_0_0: eth2 = 10.0.0.1/24 (host side), eth0 = 172.16.0.5/31, eth1 = 172.16.0.9/31.\n  - leaf_router_0_1: eth2 = 10.0.1.1/24 (host side), eth0 = 172.16.0.7/31, eth1 = 172.16.0.11/31.\n- Kernel routing tables on routers show connected prefixes and learned BGP routes for the opposite /24. Examples:\n  - leaf_router_0_0 has a BGP-learned route to 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.4 (spine_router_0_0).\n  - leaf_router_0_1 has a BGP-learned route to 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.6 (spine_router_0_0).\n- Attempts to ping between routers (leaf->leaf, spine->spine) from within those hosts returned \"Network is unreachable\" from the automated ping tool in several attempts. This indicates at least at the moment of those tests the test process couldn't route to the target addresses (but BGP sessions themselves are up — see next section).\n\n3) BGP / control-plane\n- FRR \"show ip bgp summary\" and BGP tables:\n  - All expected EBGP sessions are established (super-spine <-> spines; spines <-> leafs). Session Up times are small but consistent (all neighbors show up/down ~00:00:44 in the snapshots).\n  - Each leaf advertises its /24 to its spine; spines and super-spine have the learned routes. Example: super_spine_router_0 BGP table contains 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24 with next-hops via the two spine routers.\n  - BGP RIBs show the /24 prefixes are present everywhere and multiple path options exist (expected for this Clos design).\n- FRR routes (v4 routing table) on routers show the BGP-learned routes are installed into the RIB and selected for forwarding (B>* entries for the /24s).\n\nAnomalies and abnormal behavior\n- Asymmetric/intermittent host-to-host connectivity:\n  - pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1: 50% packet loss.\n  - pc_0_1 -> pc_0_0: no replies (timed out).\n  - These symptoms indicate either intermittent forwarding drops along the path or asymmetric forwarding such that return traffic is not reaching the source (or is being dropped/filtered).\n- Router-to-router ping tests (from the testing harness) repeatedly returned \"Network is unreachable\" for several peer-to-peer pings between spines and leafs. This is inconsistent with the observed BGP adjacency state (BGP TCP sessions exist and are healthy), which implies:\n  - Either the automated ping attempts were addressed to IPs not covered by router route table entries in the test namespace (test artifact), or\n  - There is a control/data plane mismatch affecting some types of traffic/paths but not the TCP connections used by BGP.\n- Tool-specific errors: a few ping attempts to 10.0.0.1/10.0.1.1 reported \"Device ... is not running\" from the test tool. However, the routers' interfaces are configured and UP; therefore the tool message is likely an environment/test-harness artifact rather than a definitive indication those interfaces are down.\n\nLocalization — devices/links implicated\n- Edge (leaf-to-host) plane: Because the leaves show the host-facing IPs (10.0.0.1 and 10.0.1.1) and PCs have correct default routes to them, yet host-to-host traffic is unreliable/asymmetric, the immediate suspicion localizes to one or both leaf router host-facing interfaces (leaf_router_0_0 eth2 or leaf_router_0_1 eth2) or the host NICs. Evidence:\n  - Host default routes point at the leaf eth2 addresses.\n  - Leaf eth2 interfaces are UP and have traffic counters > 0 (some traffic seen), but traffic counts are low and asymmetric.\n- Data-plane forwarding between leaves/spines: because BGP is up the control-plane path for route exchange is functional (TCP sessions established), but pings between routers failed in automated tests. This suggests a possible data-plane forwarding inconsistency on some paths/for some packet types; it implicates the inter-router links or FIB entries on routers (forwarding table discrepancies) as a secondary area to investigate.\n- Super-spine and spine routers: control-plane is healthy (they see the prefixes and BGP neighbors). No direct indication from the data collected that super-spine or spines are dropping BGP or forwarding all packets for the /24s; rather, the spines' RIBs show correct next-hops to leaves for the /24s.\n\nRoot-cause hypotheses (ranked, with supporting evidence)\n1) (Most likely) Leaf-edge forwarding or ARP/host-edge problem causing asymmetric or dropped traffic\n   - Evidence:\n     - Hosts have correct IP addresses and default routes towards leaf eth2.\n     - leaf_router eth2 interfaces are UP and have small packet counters (some RX/TX), consistent with partial traffic.\n     - Host-to-host ICMP shows asymmetry (one direction 50% loss, reverse fails) which commonly results from ARP/gateway issues, asymmetric path selection, or packet filtering on one side.\n     - BGP and inter-router routing are OK, so control-plane distribution of prefixes is not the failing element.\n   - Possible specific causes in this category: occasional ARP failures on an edge interface, host NIC issues, firewall/iptables blocking inbound ICMP on one side, misconfigured forwarding rules on the leaf, or a transient link flapping at the leaf-host interface.\n\n2) (Possible) Data-plane forwarding inconsistency between routers (FIB vs RIB mismatch or selective packet drops)\n   - Evidence:\n     - Automated pings between routers returned \"Network is unreachable\" (test harness errors). Although BGP sessions are up, an inconsistent or missing FIB entry could cause some packet types to be dropped while BGP (which established the session earlier) remains up.\n     - Routing tables show expected entries, but the \"network unreachable\" responses indicate that some test commands did not find a route, or the source host had no valid next-hop for the destination network in that test namespace.\n   - Possible specific causes: stale/missing kernel FIB entries, policy-based routing interfering with certain traffic, or incorrect next-hop resolution for specific addresses.\n\n3) (Less likely) Super-spine/spine control-plane or path-policy causing asymmetr